[[Category:OntologySync-managed-resource]]

Calcium imaging uses fluorescent indicators (chemical dyes or genetically encoded sensors like GCaMP) to visualize changes in intracellular calcium concentration, which serves as a proxy for neural activity. When a neuron fires, calcium floods the cell and the indicator fluoresces, allowing optical detection of activity across large populations of neurons simultaneously.

== Key Variants ==
* '''One-photon (widefield) calcium imaging''' — used by Miniscopes for deep-brain imaging in freely behaving animals
* '''Two-photon calcium imaging''' — higher spatial resolution, typically requires head fixation
* '''Fiber photometry''' — bulk fluorescence signal through an optical fiber, no single-cell resolution

== Relation to Miniscope ==
The Miniscope platform is designed primarily for one-photon calcium imaging in freely moving animals. A GRIN lens is implanted above the brain region of interest, and the Miniscope sits on top to capture fluorescence changes in real time.
